#X text 99 88 NYQUIST;
#X obj 536 897 metro 20;
#X obj 297 12 /usr/lib/puredata/doc/5.reference/set-dsp-tgl;
#X text 117 365 NEXT BLOCK OF OSC WILL START FROM PHASE SET;
#X msg 246 106 62;
#X msg 279 106 66;
#X text 30 676 CALCULATES FFT OF ONE BLOCK: HERE 128 SAMPLES \; ONE BLOCK GENERATED ABOVE IS AN OSCILLATOR WITH DISCERE FREQUENCY FROM [0 TO 0.5] (DISCRETE FREQUENCY INDEX FROM [0 TO 64]. WHY NOT MORE(TILL 128): NYQUIST FREQUENCY - FROM 64 TO 128 RESULT WILL BE FOLDOVER/MIRROR OF 0 TO 64 INVESTIGATE MORE..., f 47;
#X text 1261 20 128 [SAMPLES] -> [48000 SAMPLE/SEC] -> ~2.67 [MS];
#X obj 814 138 switch~ 128 1 1 0;
#X text 939 139 COULD BE USED INSTEAD OF BLOCK~;
#X text 810 36 SEEMS LIKE EVEN IF NOT SET. THE DEFAULT BLOCK SIZE OF PD IS 64 - SHOULD BE CHANGED ACCORDING TO PROCESSING WINDOW SIZE -> 128, f 47;
#X text 812 189 HOW TO GET THE DEFAULT BLOCK-SIZE IN USE?;
#X obj 536 875 bng 20 250 50 0 empty empty empty 0 -10 0 12 #fcfcfc #000000 #000000;
#X text 699 263 WHEN DISCRETE FREQUENCY INDEX = 1 (AND PHASE 0) FFT FIND THE FREQUENCY BINS AT 1 AND 127 UNDERSTAND THIS BETTER..., f 48;
#X text 876 768 [fft~] computes the Fourier transform \, given the real and imaginary part of a complex-valued signal. Here the imaginary part is zero (the input is real-valued). The output is a (real \, imaginary) pair for each frequency from 0 to 128 (in units of SR/64)., f 41;
#X text 887 900 The [fft~] object has separate inlets for the real and imaginary parts of a complex-valued signal and outputs its Fourier transform \, again using separate outlets for the real and imaginary part. The transform is done on one block of samples (here the block size is 64 \, (Pd's default is 64). The outputs give the complex amplitudes of the harmonics of the input signal \, from DC up. The harmonics are tuned to the fundamental frequency of the analysis \, 1/128th of the sample rate. If the frequency (in harmonics) is an integer \, the result is two harmonics symmetric about the Nyquist frequency. Fractional frequencies spill across harmonics. Changing the initial phase rotates energy from real to imaginary and back., f 139;
#X text 63 174 (1/128 == DISCRETE FUNDAMENTAL FREQUENCY OF ANALYSIS);
#X text 61 247 (SR/128 == CONTINUOUS FUNDAMENTAL FREQUENCY OF ANALYSIS);
#X text 698 397 TO GET CONTINUOUS FREQUENCY OF THE WINDOW BINS -> INDEX SHOULD BE MULTIPLIED BY SR/(WINDOW-SIZE), f 50;
#X obj 64 958 tabwrite~ \$0-amplitude;
